,Not Recommended,238240,17254072,"Posted: 27 July, 2015",all,Zincoshine,"OK, so early access is finally over. The tutorial system has been overhauled and when you start a world with a new char the codex screen comes up with tips and at the same time a flying shark comes and asks you for help, it's a little cluttery and overwhelming but thankfully its ok because even at night you are safe so you have time to read through everything. The new system is definetely a big step forward however the game feels extremely unpolished. There are glitches in the physics and the game has a few performance issues which is really strange. The lighting has been greatly improved but does bug out occasionally. Hopefully the game will soon be updated to polish up things a bit.With regards to recommending it.... can I? Sadly no. If a friend asks me about this game, I would just tell him/her to buy terraria. The reason for this is because for a price 50% higher than terraria, you are getting a worser game. if this game with its issues was just 7.5 dollars, then it would be a good purchase however. One might argue that terraria has had years to develop while this game has just been released. That's true, but the price of terraria is still cheaper regardless. To be fair though, terraria is a seriously underpriced game, it should cost at least 20 dollars by now, considering all the content it has.Despite the lack of recommendation, it must be stated that this game contains some really great innovations that are worthy of praise: 1) a build in link to wikipedia 2) a system that allows you to track down which materials you need to construct something. I really wish these two things were in terraria.Edit: I am surprised by how obscure it turns out this game is. Not a single official reviewer has touched the game and there is only one user review on metacritic.Edit2: While the link to the wiki itself is a great thing to have in the game, the wiki itself has barely any contect, another factor in making this game difficult to approach."
